	faithBodyHtml={`<p>Bangladesh is overwhelmingly Muslim &mdash; around 91% &mdash; with a Hindu minority of nearly 8% and a small Christian community of roughly half a million, about 0.3% of the people. It is a church that has held the faith quietly and faithfully, with the Catholic Church its largest body alongside Protestant and indigenous-minority believers.</p><p>The Bible is treasured by this faithful community. The Bengali Bible (Kitabul Mukkadas) is the most widely read, in a tradition that reaches back to William Carey&rsquo;s Bengali Scripture of 1801 &mdash; though for most Bangladeshis, the Bible has never been opened.</p><p>That is Bangladesh&rsquo;s deep need: that the poor, the flood-struck, the searching &mdash; and the faithful church that has endured &mdash; would know God not only as the Almighty, but as a near and loving <em>Father</em>. That is what a fresh translation can reveal.</p>`}
